content.description: This is the first crack system on the left side of the east face. It becomes a chimney near the top. It's has a strenuous start. All in all a good warm-up for a day's climbing.

Starts at the right end of the East Face of Trashcan Rock, facing the road and at the back of a small cove of rock. The very rightmost crack, just a few feet left of Left Sawdust Crack. A short, clean hand crack on good rock but a little meat-tenderizer inside. Not too bad though. Leans a little left and is a touch awkward for the grade but nothing to worry about. Not terribly memorable but a good warmup if you're in the area.

Just to the left of Right Sawdust crack, climb the thinner and much more difficult crack, avoiding using Right Sawdust crack at the top where it gets a little cruxy. Not too bad though, just move fast enough to avoid the pump. Would be worth another star if it wasn't so close to Right Sawdust Crack, at the top it could be pretty tempting to use the other crack just 2-3' away.
content.protection: Thin to hand sized. Best to have a couple of fist sized pieces for an anchor.

content.description:
This crack, just to the left of

Butterfly Crack

(5.11c), begins with a bulge. Good stances above the bulge make gear placement relatively easy until the dihedral crux section. The crux is very difficult to protect because the crack becomes very shallow. However, the rock is solid and edges are numerous on both sides of the dihedral. Above the crux the crack widens to 2" and takes bomber cam placements. A serious lead on excellent rock (3 out of 5 stars).
content.protection: Small to medium stoppers and small TCU's to 2" cams protect this crack of varying width and depth. Large cams make a solid anchor at the top. An easy walkoff can be found on the west face or north end of the rock.

content.description: This is a short, unprotected face route.  It starts on a boulder to the left of Filch on the south face
A clean, very shallow offwidth leads to a thin hands crack above.  This is a good place to practice heel-toe jams.
content.protection: standard rack - the offwidth has a thin crack in the back that you can place protection in
content.location: middle of the narrow south face of the rock

content.description:
This is between Hermanutic and the Sawdust cracks.  Greasy tips locks lead to a juggy hand crack.  Good rock.

The protection is maybe PG- bomber, but it's too strenuous to place it until you're a ways up.
